VERDICT: not-confirmed
REASON: The oracle would fail and the PoC's assertions would fire on unfixed code — both the invariant gap (src/thread.rs:69-71 Thread::inv only checks priority.inv) and the unconditional `is_metairq: false` in Thread::new (lines 83-89) are factually present. But the finding is not interesting. The report's `NUM_METAIRQ_PRIORITIES` is invented by the validator, not defined in gale; the actual production boundary is the FFI in ffi/src/lib.rs (e.g., gale_sched_should_preempt lines 5245-5262 and gale_k_sched_next_up_decide 5298-5327), which takes `candidate_is_metairq: u32` / `runq_best_is_metairq: u32` as pre-classified booleans extracted by Zephyr's C-side `thread_is_metairq(thread)` (zephyr/gale_sched.c:195-199,230). The Rust `Thread` struct is a verification/model surface — no production caller constructs it (`Thread::new` has zero callers in src/ or ffi/src/; only test helpers in tests/sched_integration.rs:839-844 use it). The PoC (B) establishes drift by caller-side mutation of a pub field in test code, which is exactly how the model is intended to be populated for scenario coverage; in the live system the C classifier cannot produce drift. Strengthening `Thread::inv()` to tie `is_metairq` to priority is a reasonable hygiene improvement but does not close any path from the kernel boundary to H-1: no verified scheduling function produces `Thread`s, and the FFI carries booleans that are already the C truth. Secondary blocker: `safety/stpa/ucas.yaml` does not exist — artifacts/stpa.yaml:12-13 explicitly scopes UCAs out for the initial artifact, so there is no UCA to map to; the report itself concedes this at its tail. This is a documentation/invariant-tightening suggestion at most, not a scheduler-integrity finding on the verified surface.
